{
  "answer": "**The dream-narrative poem is \"Maa ka Khwab\" (\"Mother's Dream\"), chapter 29 of *Bang-E-Dara Part 1* by Allama Iqbal.**[^1]\n\nThis poem is voiced by a grieving mother who dreams of a procession of boys in \"robes of emerald green arrayed, / a burning lamp each hand displayed,\" with her dead son walking at the back, \"his pace ... slow, / and in his hand, no lamp did glow.\" She reproaches him for abandoning her, and he replies with the closing two lines:\n\n> \\\"Do you now now see what has become of it?  \n> It is your tears that have extinguished it.\\\"[^2]\n\n[^1]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, ch. 29 [\"Maa ka Khwab\"](https://falsafa-corpus.org/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/29-maa-ka-khwab/translation/).\n\n[^2]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, ch. 29 [\"Maa ka Khwab\"](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/29-maa-ka-khwab/translation/#p-4feffc).",
